==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Moulder
<hw>Mould"er</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Moldered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or
<conjf>Mouldered</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Moldering</conjf> or <conjf>Mouldering</conjf>.]</vmorph>
<ety>[From <er>Mold</er> fine soft earth: cf. Prov. G.
<ets>multern</ets>.]</ety> <def>To crumble into small particles; to turn
to dust by natural decay; to lose form, or waste away, by a gradual
separation of the component particles, without the presence of water; to
crumble away.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>moldering</qex> of earth in frosts and sun.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When statues <qex>molder</qex>, and when arches fall.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If he had sat still, the enemy's army would have
<qex>moldered</qex> to nothing.</q> <rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moulder</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Molder</ent>⟦br⟧
